06653nam a22008775i 9781477302330DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014046939  a97814773023307 a10.7560/3023232doi  a(DE-B1597)587785  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHQ76.8.U5bQ44 2015 4aHQ76.8.U5bQ44 2015 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.76089/6807322300aQueer Brown Voices :bPersonal Narratives of Latina/o LGBT Activism /ced. by Uriel Quesada, Salvador Vidal-Ortiz, Letitia Gomez. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (238 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. BROWN WRITING QUEER: A COMPOSITE OF LATINA/O LGBT ACTIVISM -- tDancing at the Crossroads: Mulata, Mestiza, Macha, Mujer -- tWe Are a Part of the History of Texas That You Must Not Exclude! -- tFrom the Closet to LGBT Radio Host in Dallas -- tAn East L.A. Warrior Who Bridged the Latina/o and the Gay Worlds -- tA South Texas Activist in Washington, D.C., Houston, and San Antonio -- tThe Boy in Fear Who Became a Latino/a LGBT Advocate in Philadelphia -- tNo te rajes—Don’t Back Down! Daring to Be Out and Visible -- tCreating Spaces to Break the Circle of Silence and Denial -- tThe Queer Roots of the Esperanza Peace and Justice Center in San Antonio, Texas -- tLatinas/os and the AIDS Treatment Advocacy Movement -- tWe Must Preserve Our Latina/o LGBT History -- tAll the Identities on the Table: Power, Feminism, and LGBT Activism in Puerto Rico -- tVisibility, Inclusivity, and the Fight for LGBT Rights in New England -- tFinding a Home in Transgender Activism in San Francisco -- tCONCLUSION -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the last three decades of the twentieth century, LGBT Latinas/os faced several forms of discrimination. The greater Latino community did not often accept sexual minorities, and the mainstream LGBT movement expected everyone, regardless of their ethnic and racial background, to adhere to a specific set of priorities so as to accommodate a “unified” agenda. To disrupt the cycle of sexism, racism, and homophobia that they experienced, LGBT Latinas/os organized themselves on local, state, and national levels, forming communities in which they could fight for equal rights while simultaneously staying true to both their ethnic and sexual identities. Yet histories of LGBT activism in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s often reduce the role that Latinas/os played, resulting in misinformation, or ignore their work entirely, erasing them from history. Queer Brown Voices is the first book published to counter this trend, documenting the efforts of some of these LGBT Latina/o activists. Comprising essays and oral history interviews that present the experiences of fourteen activists across the United States and in Puerto Rico, the book offers a new perspective on the history of LGBT mobilization and activism. The activists discuss subjects that shed light not only on the organizations they helped to create and operate, but also on their broad-ranging experiences of being racialized and discriminated against, fighting for access to health care during the HIV/AIDS epidemic, and struggling for awareness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGay activistszUnited States. 0aHispanic American sexual minoritiesxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aSexual minoritiesxIdentity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAcosta, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAgosto-Rosario, Moisés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCháirez, Jesús, econtributor.4c